## Named Parameters

| Parameter | Type | Default | Purpose |
|-----------|------|---------|---------|
| `populations` | LIST(VARCHAR) | *(required)* | Population label per sample, positionally aligned with .psam |
| `method` | VARCHAR | `'hudson'` | FST estimator: `'hudson'` or `'wc'` (Weir-Cockerham) |
| `pvar` | VARCHAR | auto-discovered | Explicit .pvar/.bim path |
| `psam` | VARCHAR | auto-discovered | Explicit .psam/.fam path |
| `samples` | LIST(VARCHAR) or LIST(INTEGER) | all | Filter to specific samples |
| `region` | VARCHAR | all | Filter to genomic region |

### Population Label Input

Following the "big/small data separation" principle (P1-006 §3.1), population
labels are small data (one label per sample). At biobank scale (10M samples),
this is ~100MB as a DuckDB list — well within the typed-value approach.

Labels can come from:
- **Literal list**: `populations := ['POP_A', 'POP_B', ...]`
- **Variable**: `SET VARIABLE pops = (SELECT list(pop) FROM ...)`
- **Subquery** (when supported): `populations := (SELECT list(pop) FROM ...)`

